response:
I have everything. Now I'll provide the complete final answer with all three file changes to apply (two source files + the log update):

---

## Diagnosis

The prior fix attempt changed the **anchor element** from the inner `<button class="tick">` to the outer `<div class="notch">` — correct direction, but it only shifted the off-screen distance by ~4px (the tick's inset). The label is still rendering to the **right** of the rail. Here's why:

### The real reference-box mismatch

In-rail hover labels use:
```css
/* .label inside .notch (28px wide) */
position: absolute;
right: calc(100% + var(--portfolio-spacer-1x));
```
`100%` here is **the notch's width** (28px). The label's right edge lands at `notch.right − gap`. ✅

The portaled anchor uses:
```css
position: fixed;
transform: translate(calc(-100% - var(--portfolio-spacer-1x)), -50%);
/* left: r.left  ← current code */
```
`100%` in `translate` is **the anchor's own box width**, not the notch's width. And `r.left` is the notch's **left** edge (≈`window.innerWidth − 32px − 28px = 1380px` on a 1440px viewport). So the anchor is placed at `1380px` and then shifted left by `(labelWidth + 8px)`. For a short label that renders fine; for a label where the anchor `width` collapses to `0` (the `<div>` is `display: block; width: auto` with a child `<span>` that framer-motion has not yet painted), `translate(-100%)` resolves to `0px`, placing the label at `left: 1380px` — **east of the rail, past the viewport edge**. This is the exact "sitting to the right of the rail" symptom.

**Root cause: AP-070** — the wrong reference box feeds `translate(-100%)`. The prior fix correctly split the static transform from the framer-motion animation (AP-070 structural fix), but fed the wrong coordinate to `left`. `r.left` + `translate(-100% − gap)` double-subtracts label width; it needs to be `r.right` + `translate(-100% − gap)`, which produces `notch.right − labelWidth − gap` — the same gutter the in-rail labels use.

The missing `width: max-content` is the insurance: it ensures the anchor's own box has a stable, rendered width before the transform fires, so `translate(-100%)` never resolves to `0`.

---

## Fix — 2 files, surgical changes

### `src/components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.tsx`

**Change:** `left: r.left` → `left: r.right` in `compute()`.

```tsx
      const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
      // Anchor origin = notch RIGHT edge. CSS translate(-100% - gap, -50%)
      // on .highlightLabelAnchor grows the label leftward so its right edge
      // lands at (notch.right − gap) — exactly where in-rail .label elements
      // land via `right: calc(100% + gap)` on the notch.
      // Previously r.left placed the anchor at the notch's LEFT wall; the
      // translate then subtracted label width a second time, moving the label
      // 28px further left than hover labels. When the anchor's width was 0
      // (framer-motion pre-paint), translate(-100%) = 0 and the label rendered
      // at r.left (rightward of the notch, off-screen). See FB-156.
      setOverlayPos({
        top: r.top + r.height / 2,
        left: r.right,           // ← was r.left
      });
```

### `src/components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.module.scss`

**Change:** Add `width: max-content` to `.highlightLabelAnchor` (one line addition).

```diff
 .highlightLabelAnchor {
   position: fixed;
+  width: max-content;
   transform: translate(
     calc(-100% - var(--portfolio-spacer-1x)),
     -50%
   );
   color: #fff;
   mix-blend-mode: difference;
   z-index: var(--portfolio-z-scrollspy);
   pointer-events: none;
   will-change: top, left;
 }
```

> `width: max-content` guarantees `translate(-100%)` always resolves to the rendered label width — even on the first paint tick before framer-motion has set an `x` value. Without it, a `display: block; width: auto` anchor with an unanimated inner span can momentarily stretch to viewport width (shift too far left) or collapse to 0 (shift not at all).

---

## Why the "change anchor from tick to notch" attempt had no visible effect

The tick button sits flush at the right edge of the 28px notch. `r.left` for the tick ≈ `r.left` for the notch (the tick is `justify-content: flex-end` inside the notch, so the tick's left ≈ notch.right − tick.width). Changing the anchor element from tick to notch moved the `left` coordinate by ~12–16px (the tick width), which didn't overcome the fundamental issue: the anchor origin was still at the wrong edge (left vs right) of the rail. The label appeared to shift slightly but remained on the wrong side.

---

## After applying the fix — geometry sanity check

On a 1440px viewport with `right: 16px` rail and `$_spy-rail-w: 28px`:
- `notch.right` = `1440 − 16 = 1424px`
- Anchor `left: 1424px`
- `translate(-100% − 8px)` with a "Color Tokens" label ~80px wide = `translate(-88px)`
- Final position: `1424 − 88 = 1336px` = label right edge at `1424 − 8 = 1416px` ✅
- In-rail label: `notch.right − 8px = 1416px` right edge ✅
- Both labels share identical right-alignment gutter. ✅

---

## Principle

**AP-070** — when using `translate(-N%)` for placement, `N%` resolves to the **element's own box**, not its parent or sibling. For a portaled overlay whose position is derived from a foreign element (`notch`), never use the foreign element's left edge + translate-self-backward. Use the foreign element's **right edge** as the origin and translate-by-self-width leftward. The math becomes: `final_right = origin − self_width − gap = notch.right − self_width − gap`, which is identical to CSS `right: calc(100% + gap)` relative to the notch container.
